The catecholic substrates caffeic acid and eriodictyol were converted by \pfomt much more quickly than \ifa, which is a (3-hydroxy-4-methoxy)-substituted cinnamic acid (\autoref{fig:e_pHprofile}).

The highest specific activity $A_\mathrm{sp}$ for \ifa conversion was two orders of magnitude lower than the highest activity for the conversion of the other two substrates.
Nonetheless, conversion was observed for \ifa with increasing pH and even an influence of magnesium was observed (\autoref{fig:e_pHprofile} and \autoref{tab:specific.activity}).
\textit{Iso}-ferulic acid was converted rather slowly without the addition of \cf{Mg^2+} ($A_\mathrm{sp}=$\SI{7}{\pico\katal\per\milli\gram}).
However, addition of \SI{10}{\milli\molar} \cf{Mg^2+} increased the rate of \ifa conversion by 3-fold, from \SI{7}{\pico\katal\per\milli\gram} to \SI{21}{\pico\katal\per\milli\gram} at pH 9.45 (\autoref{tab:specific.activity}). 

The specific activities observed for the conversion of caffeic acid are comparable to published data \citep{Dippe2015}.
For the two catecholic substrates, the pH-optimum shifted from neutral to alkaline pHs, when \cf{Mg^2+} was omitted.
However, the maximum activity remained roughly the same, even though magnesium addition seemed to have a slight rate increasing effect.
Rate enhancements of up to 3-fold were observed at pH 9.45, when \cf{Mg^2+} was omitted compared to when it was present.
The maximum activities without magnesium were observed at pH 9.45 with \SI{1466}{\pico\katal\per\milli\gram} and \SI{824}{\pico\katal\per\milli\gram} for caffeic acid and eriodictyol respectively, while with \SI{10}{\milli\molar} \cf{Mg^2+} the maximum activities were recorded at pH 6.5 and increased to \SI{1572}{\pico\katal\per\milli\gram} and \SI{1354}{\pico\katal\per\milli\gram} respectively.
