The smallest $p$-value 0.0030 was calculated for the interaction factor \factorx{pH}$\times$\factorx{Mg}, and strongly suggests that there is a significant interaction between methylation activity on \ifa and \cf{Mg^2+} addition combined with pH-modulation.
The parameter estimate $\beta_3$ for this term is almost 374.
Since in this case \factorx{Mg} is categorical and can only be 0 (no magnesium added) or 1 (magnesium added) the interaction term $\beta_3\times$\factorx{pH}$\times$\factorx{Mg} resolves to 0, if no magnesium was added.
This means that when \cf{Mg^2+} is added, the activity (in $\mathrm{AU\,min^{-1}}$) is increased by 374 for each unit the pH is raised.
The $p$-value for \factorx{pH} as a main effect is rather high, suggesting pH alone has no significant impact on the activity.
The parameter estimate $\beta_1$ for factor \factorx{Mg} however has a low $p$-value of 0.010, which suggest that its impact on activity is significant. 
Due to the categorical nature of \factorx{Mg}, this means, that the activity is decreased by \num{2201} $\mathrm{AU\,min^{-1}}$ when magnesium is added.
However, this information is only of importance when predicting the activity outside of the measured pH range, which was not the aim here.
Together, these results illustrate, that neither magnesium addition, nor the pH alone would have such a strong effect on the activity as both factors combined had.

The data of the second subset containing of the catecholic substrates was also modelled in a similar fashion (see \autoref{sec:apppfomtph}).
It was found, that the pH has a much stronger influence on the methylation activity of PFOMT towards catechols than \ifa.
Interaction between magnesium addition and pH-modulation were also suggested for the catecholic substrates from this data.
For a more thourough discussion see \autoref{sec:apppfomtph}.
In addition to pure inference based modelling, models can also be used to make predictions based on (new) independent variables (\autoref{fig:e_pHlm}).
However, it cannot be stressed enough that models do not reflect the truth, but are rather another tool to gain insight into a system.
